liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Courtney Barrett Peters The second government-assisted charter flight carrying Australians home from Israel will land at Sydney Airport later this evening. Some 284 passengers are on board the Qantas airlines (QF310) flight, flying from London via Dubai after being evacuated from Tel Aviv in recent days. Home-made teddy bears were left by the Red Cross for the 50 children travelling with their families. The plane was scheduled to land at 7:05pm is now tracking for an 8:30pm arrival.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Second government-assisted flight from Israel due to land in Sydney

children.content: Reporting by Courtney Barrett Peters
The second government-assisted charter flight carrying Australians home from Israel will land at Sydney Airport later this evening.
Some 284 passengers are on board the Qantas airlines (QF310) flight, flying from London via Dubai after being evacuated from Tel Aviv in recent days.
Home-made teddy bears were left by the Red Cross for the 50 children travelling with their families.
The plane was scheduled to land at 7:05pm is now tracking for an 8:30pm arrival.

props.alt: An image of knitted teddy bears

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Israeli government has announced what it has described as a "humanitarian zone" in southern Gaza. In statements just published on X, the government's unit responsible for the "Coordination of Government Activities in the Territories" (COGAT) said Israel's defence forces has called on Gaza residents to evacuate to an area near the city of Khan Younis. "The IDF calls on #GazaCity residents to evacuate south for their protection," COGAT said on X. "Al-Mawasi is where international #HumanitarianAid will be provided as needed." According to the United Nations' Economic and Social Commission for Western Asia, Al-Mawasi "is a Bedouin Palestinian town on the southern coast of the Gaza Strip, approximately one kilometre wide and 14 kilometres long".
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Israel announces 'humanitarian zone' in southern Gaza

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese commented on the Gaza hospital blast during a joint press conference with Fijian Prime Minister Sitiveni Rabuka, who is visiting Canberra. "We have seen a devastating loss of innocent life since the attacks on Israel by the terrorist group Hamas," Mr Albanese said. "The scenes from the explosion at a Gaza City hospital are deeply distressing and it is clear that there has been a devastating loss of life. "Every innocent life matters, whether it is Israeli or Palestinian. "Our thoughts are with those killed, those injured and their loved ones. The protection of civilian lives must come first, as the parliament said in its resolution that we carried on Monday, and respect for international humanitarian law is paramount. "We condemn any indiscriminate attacks and targeting of civilian infrastructure, including hospitals and Australia joins with others in calling for international law to always be upheld."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Anthony Albanese says 'every innocent life matters'

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Port Adelaide's ruckapalooza is complete. Port Adelaide have traded pick 50 to the Western Bulldogs for Jordon Sweet. A very simple one in the end, with that pick 50 being the one that came back to Port from Richmond in the Ivan Soldo deal. Will be very interesting to see if Port now play two rucks next year, or if Sweet has headed to another club where he'll have to play second fiddle and earn his place.
